<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-208-486  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 208 486.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 5 1990 v24 n10 p73(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>4GLs, bundled or a la carte. (fourth generation language)(includes related article on use of Structured QueryLanguage)(Product Spotlight: DBMS)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robins, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A growing trend for vendors is to separate a fourth generationlanguage from its data base management system (DBMS) for thepurpose of using another; however the advantages of doing this arestill debatable.andP;  According to a survey, 68 percent of 425 usersof relational DBMSs on medium and large-sized platforms said thatthey used development tools provided by the DBMS vendor, not byother vendors.andP;  In general, observers agree that the bundledoption is a more conservative way to go.andP;  With large systems,however, a solution may depend upon whether the DBMS is from asoftware or hardware vendor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fourth-Generation LanguagesEnhancementsData base management systemsBundled SoftwareUser Needs.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>